          "body": "Verse 3 is the most important verse in the chapter, and it appears before the siege begins. 'Through the anger of the LORD this came about in Jerusalem and Judah until He cast them out from His presence.' The grammar is notable — the fall of Jerusalem is presented as the out-working of divine anger that had been building across the entire period of Judah's covenant unfaithfulness. Nebuchadnezzar is not the subject of verse 3; the LORD is. The Babylonian armies are the mechanism, but the agency belongs to YHWH. This is the theological framework that makes the chapter not merely history but Scripture. Without verse 3, the fall of Jerusalem is a military tragedy. With verse 3, it is the precise enactment of Deuteronomy 28:36 and 64 — the covenant curse for persistent rebellion, executed by the covenant God."
