          "title": "The fate of Zedekiah — a name that became an indictment",
          "body": "Zedekiah means 'the LORD is my righteousness,' but verse 2 delivers its verdict in the chapter's first breath: 'He did evil in the sight of the LORD.' The narrative of his capture and punishment (vv. 7-11) is structured as tragic irony. He fled by night — the king of Jerusalem sneaking through a back gate under cover of darkness (v. 7). He was overtaken at Jericho — the city where Israel's conquest of the land began, now the city where the last king's freedom ends. At Riblah, Nebuchadnezzar passed sentence. The sentence was maximally designed: his sons were killed before his eyes (v. 10), and then his eyes were put out (v. 11). The last thing Zedekiah ever saw was the execution of his children. Then he was bound in bronze, taken to Babylon, and imprisoned until the day of his death (v. 11). Swindoll observed that this is judgment that matches the crime precisely — a king who refused to see the truth of Jeremiah's words is left with nothing to see at all."
